




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Interaction of Judgemental and Statistical Forecasting Methods: Issues & Analysis
AU  - Bunn, Derek
AU  - Wright, George
Y1  - 1991/05/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.37.5.501
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.37.5.501
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 501
EP  - 518
VL  - 37
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper reviews several of the current controversies in the relative value of judgemental and statistical forecasting methods. Where expert, informed judgemental forecasts are being used, a critical analysis of the evidence suggests that their quality is higher than many researchers have previously asserted, and circumstances favourable to this are identified. The issue of the interaction of judgemental and statistical methods is, however, identified as a more worthwhile line of inquiry, and research in this area is reviewed, differentiating approaches aimed at synthesising both of these inputs.
AB  - This paper reviews several of the current controversies in the relative value of judgemental and statistical forecasting methods. Where expert, informed judgemental forecasts are being used, a critical analysis of the evidence suggests that their quality is higher than many researchers have previously asserted, and circumstances favourable to this are identified. The issue of the interaction of judgemental and statistical methods is, however, identified as a more worthwhile line of inquiry, and research in this area is reviewed, differentiating approaches aimed at synthesising both of these inputs.
